{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601676/1938010801/0648.xml":{"full_text":"THE EVENING STAR\nWith Sunday Morning Edition\n\nTHEODORE W. NOYES, Editor\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\nSATURDAY....January 8. 19S8\nThe Evening Star Newspaper Company\nMam Office: 11th St. and Pennsylvania Ave.\nNew York Office: 110 East 42nd 6t.\nChicago Office: 435 North Michigan Ave.\nDelivered by Carrier\u2014City and Suburban\nRegular Edition\nEvening and Sunday.fi5c per mo. or 15c per week\nThe Evening Star_45c per mo. or 10c per week\nThe Sunday Star._5c per copy\nNight Final Edition\nNight Pinal and Sunday Star_70c per month\nNight Pinal Star--65c per month\nCollection made at the end of each month or\ntech week. Orders may be sent by mall or tele\nphone National 6000.\nRate by Mail\u2014Payable in Advance\nMaryland and Virginia\nDaily and Sunday...1 yr., $10.00; 1 mo., 85c\nDally only-1 yr.. $\u00ab.O0; 1 mo.. 50c\nSunday only-1 yr., $4.00; 1 mo.. 40c\nAll Other States and Canada\nDally and Sunday.l yr\u201e $12.00; 1 mo., $1.00\nDally only-1 yr., $8.00; 1 mo.. 75c\nSunday only-1 yr\u201e $5.00; 1 mo.. 60c\nMember of the Associated Press\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to\nf.or republication ol all news dispatches\ncredited to it or not otherwise credited in this\nSTiP*.r, Wd \u2018l60 loc*' news published herein.\nAll rights of publication of special dispatches\nherein also are reserved.\nProduction Control.\nPresident Roosevelt, speaking at the\nJackson Day dinner here tonight, is ex\npected to enlighten the country further\nregarding his plans for attacking the\nbusiness recession. In his message on\nthe state of the Union delivered to Con\ngress in person last Monday, the Presi\ndent said he would deal with his recom\nmendations regarding monopoly and\nbusiness practices in a later special mes\nsage. The following day, at a press con\nference, the President intimated that\nwhat was needed was control of produc\ntion in industry, so as to prevent as far\nas possible a glut of the market. He in\ncluded in this proposed control some\nmeasure of restriction on the overselling\nof a product to the general public.\nHere is an idea that smacks strongly\nof the crop control plan which the Pres\nident has proposed for the farmers. He\nhas not suggested that industry should\nreceive benefit payments from the Gov\nernment for complying with a produc\ntion control program\u2014as the farmers do\nwhen they agree to control their produc\ntion. Just how he will seek the com\npliance of manufacturers, and in turn\nthe industrial workers, in a production\ncontrol program has not yet been dis\nclosed. Possibly some measure of price\nfixing will be the sugar bait.\nThe President has intimated that the\nIndustrial producers should sit down\naround the table with the Government\nand agree upon plans for production\ncontrol. Any such agreement would be\nIn effect collusion, particularly if prices\nwere mentioned. What becomes of the\nfree competition and the' anti-trust\nlaws under such a regime? It is true\nthat the President continues to stress\nthe need of competition\u2014fair competi\ntion\u2014but how any competition could or\nwould exist under the suggested pro\nduction control plan it is impossible to\nunderstand.\nThere is small wonder that business,\nboth big and little, is puzzled and rubs\nits eyes in amazement as the succeed\ning days reveal the divergent ideas of\nadministration and New Deal spokes\nmen. The President is to speak\nto the whole country tonight, and he\nmay be more revealing of his plans for\nbusiness and the recession. Six mem\nbers of his cabinet, at least, are to\naddress other Jackson Day dinners in\nwidely separated sections of the coun\ntry, and still other officials of the Gov\nernment speak in other places. Surely\n(rom this great mass utterance, the\nadministration should be able to give\nthe country an idea of what is in store\nfor it. The danger is that all the\nspeakers may not strike the same note\nor sing the same tune. The country,\nhowever, will listen particularly to the\nPresident for the dominating note.\nt m\nIt will be interesting to recall some ol\nthe things George Ade wrote and see\nwhether Louis Ludlow can apply them\nto current purposes. We still have the\n\u201cLallapaloosa\u201d whose \"Line of Talk\u201d is\nmore influential than ever.\nKipling was wrong when he said \u201cEast\nis East and West is t^pst and never the\ntwain shall meet.\u201d It is evident that they\nhave met, with a reminder that there are\ncertain human obligations that must be\nrespected.\nAction on Taxes.\nStraying from the subject of unem\nployment alone as the committee showed\nan obvious desire to hear his views on\nkindred matters, Chairman Eccles of the\nFederal Reserve Board, testifying before\nthe Byrnes Committee the other day, ex\npressed some views on taxation which\nshould be encouraging to business senti\nment.\nObviously leaning away from much of\nthe extreme position of some of the New\nDeal spokesmen, the Utah financier lent\nhis unqualified support to those who\nhave called for amendment of the un\ndistributed corporate profits tax and the\ntax on capital gains. With regard to\nthe first, Mr. Eccles said he believed\nexemption should be allowed for profits\nto be used In plant expansion and that\nadequate allowance should be given for\nstatutory or contractual obligations of\ncorporations.\nExamination of corporate income sta\ntistics shows that a moderate fixed ex\nemption of profits within the first $20,000\nwould remove this burdensome tax from\ngreat majority of the Nation\u2019s corpora\ntions but would affect only about ten\nper cent of the aggregate profits now\ntaxable. Thus, the alleviation would\ntruly benefit those concerns which are\nmost in need of their net income for\nreinvestment purposes.\nMaking clear that he did not blame\nthis corporate profits tax far the present\nbusiness decline and that he would not\nfavor its outright repeal, Mr. Eccles\nturned to the capital gains and losses\ntax with equal candor. Here again he\nspecified that he felt that the principle\nof taxing capital gains as income is a\nJuA one but that he agreed with critics\nwho feel that allowance should be made\nfor carrying capital losses over a period\nof years sufficient to allow their bal\nancing against the taxable capital gains.\nAt the present time the prohibition\nagainst carrying capital losses beyond a\nsingle tax year is obviously one-sided\nas compared to the taxability of capital\ngains accrued over any length of time.\nMr. Eccles\u2019 voice Is just one of many,\nboth within and outside the Govern\nment, that have been raised in favor of\nrevising these two taxes. During the\nspecial session last fall the House Ways\nand Means Committee reported consid\nerable progress toward riuch revision.\nPresident Roosevelt indicated in his\nopening message to Congress this week\nthat he believes some tax corrections\nare advisable. Let action be taken then\nas soon as possible in order that those\nwho feel the restrictive effects of these\nlevies may have a \"bird in hand\u201d rather\nthan promises \"in the bush.\u201d\nCheap Life Insurance.\nPresident Roosevelt's budget for the\nfiscal year 1939, now before Congress,\ncalls for a round $1,000,000,000 for the\nArmy and Navy\u2014highest annual na\ntional defense expenditure in our peace\ntime history. It is a lot of money. It is\na proper cause for anxiety to already\noverburdened taxpayers, as it is to the\nPresident himself. Announcing that he\nmay find it advisable to recommend even\nadditional appropriations for naval ex\npansion, Mr. Roosevelt indicates that he\ncontemplates such action with reluctance,\nbut, because he is filled with \"growing\nconcern\u201d over \"a world of high tension\nand disorder\u2014a world where stable civili\nzation is actually threatened,\u201d he rightly\nconsiders that the American people have\nno alternative but \"to keep ourselves ade\nquately strong in self-defense.\u201d Sagely,\nwe are adjured, \"facts are facts, and\nAmerica must recognize them.\u201d\nIn the same message to Congress in\nwhich the President pleaded the cause of\npeace by preparedness, he mentioned that\nth^ country\u2019s income was raised from\n$38,000,000,000 in 1932 to about $68,000,\n000,000 in 1937. \"Our objective,\u201d he add\ned, \u201cis to raise it to ninety or one hundred\nbillion dollars.\u201d Leaving the last-named\nsomewhat astronomical figures out of ac\ncount, and assuming that income is des\ntined to remain at or about $70,000,000,\n000, a defense budget of $1,000,000,000 is\nalmost trifling by comparison. Put in\nterms of national life insurance of an\namount equivalent to national income,\nwe are paying an annual premium of a\nbare fraction of one per cent for protec\ntion of 130,000,000 American lives, of our\nvast continental domain and far-flung\ncoasts, of our overseas possessions, and\nof our seaborne foreign trade. The air\nis thick with talk of recovery, and of\nways and means for achieving it. Re\ncovery, if it came overnight, would not be\nw\u2019orth the paper on which it was statis\ntically recorded, if we did not possess the\nmeans of guaranteeing the safety of the\nhuman, physical and territorial values\nwhich are the United States of America,\nand for the sake of which recovery is\nsought.\nSo, far from shuddering at the prospect\nof having to spend more hundreds of\nmillions, or perhaps, eventually, even\nseveral additional billions, on fortifying\nourselves on land and sea and in the\nair\u2014particularly afloat and aloft\u2014we\nshould congratulate ourselves that our\nnational life insurance premium, meas\nured against the fabulously larger\namount at stake, is truly insignificant.\nWhat President Roosevelt tells the world,\nthough in no spirit of bravado or bellig\nerency, is well typified by that famous\njingle of Victorian Britain:\n\"We don\u2019t want to fight,\nBut, by jingo, if we do,\nWe\u2019ve got the men,\nWe've got the ships,\nAnd we\u2019ve got the money, too!\"\nwnen Mr. Ludlow quotes George Ade\nhe brings to attention standards of\nAmerican humor which do not neces\nsarily coincide with standards of Amer\nican statesmanship. Some of the capital\nthings Mr. Ade used to write would be\nwell worthy of attention if Mr. Ludlow\nhad not permitted Indiana talents to\novercrowd the scene.\nAmerican aviators charge $1.50 for a\n10-minute passenger flight and may not\nbe able to collect even that much when\nquestions of the hop-field as a local\nnuisance are finally decided.\nA World Medical Center.\nThe proposed naval medical center,\nwhich now seems near to realization\nwith a preliminary provision of $4,850,\n000 in the current budget, is significant\nboth in itself and in respect to the\nlarger pattern into which it fits.\nIt will constitute a very large unit in\na development, in progress without at\ntracting much attention for some years,\nwhich is making Washington the medi\ncal capital of the world. Other units\nare the National Institute of Health of\nthe Public Health Service, the great\nArmy medical center which has grown\nup around Walter Reed Hospital, the\nagricultural research center at Beltsville,\nwhere many experiments have dealt with\nfundamental medical problems; the In\nstitute of Pharmacy, the diagnostic cen\nter of the Veterans\u2019 Administration at\nMount Alto and such older institutions\nas the surgeon general\u2019s library. Only\nsecond in importance is the great ex\npansion and improvement in the past\nfew years of the three local medical\nschools, George Washington, George\ntown and Howard. The first two espe\ncially have becorap far more than insti\ntutions for the systematic education of\nphysicians. They have become world\ncenters of research. A striking example\nof this expansion Is the Brain Institute\nk\nrecently established at Georgetown for\npure research in brain physiology and\nanatomy. Almost unnoticed in this de\nvelopment has been the establishment\nthis year of the William A. White School\nof Psychiatry, which promises to raise\nWashington above Vienna as a world\ncenter for research in this branch of\nmedicine.\nThe activities of these units is at pres\nent unco-ordinated and there is no im\nmediate proposal to co-ordinate them.\nPerhaps the best Interests of all will be\nserved if each pursues its individual\nway in an atmosphere of friendly co\noperation.\nThe fact remains that in the field of\nmedical research America has arrived.\nVienna and Paris have lost their\nprestige in this respect. They began\nsligping after the war. And of all this\nAmerican development Washington has\nbecome, without any conscious design\non the part of anybody, the center which\nhenceforth may be expected to attract\nstudents from all over the world.\nPublic School Jurisdiction.\nA nice legal question has arisen with\nthe apparent interpretation of a legis\nlative rider by the Commissioners to\ngive them control over school custodial\npersonnel and the refusal of the Board\nof Education to recognize such interpre\ntation.\nThe rider in question, attached to the\nhealth center item in the current District\nAppropriation Act, declares that \"all\nbuildings belonging to the District\u201d are\nto be under the \u201cjurisdiction and con\ntrol\" of the Commissioners.\nInasmuch as the Commissioners have\nnamed a committee to consider the\nappointment of custodial employes under\nthis provision and have made a school\nofficer a member of the committee, school\nofficials have assumed that an attempt\nwill be made to regulate Janitors in the\nschool buildings.\nThe question is: Does this rider on\na health item repeal the organic act of\n1906 which vests control of the public\nschools in the Board of Education?\nThe board feels emphatically that It\ndoes not. The non-specific nature of the\nrider, in which no mention is made of\nthe public schools or of the specific vest\ning of authority over the schools in the\nboard by the act of 1906, lends credence\nto this view. The Board of Education\nhas controlled the appointment of the\ncustodial personnel for more than thirty\nyears under this latter legislation, even\nthough actual title to the majority of\nthe school buildings is in the District\ngovernment.\nIn any event, the raising of the issue\nis unfortunate as it seems scarcely prob\nable that the Commissioners are serious\nly interpreting this rider as a repeal of\nthe previous law and the only result has\nbeen to revive the issue between the\nFranklin Building and the District Build\ning over the control of the local school\nsystem.\nHaving seen how they work, Mr. Dodd,\nthe retiring Ambassador to Germany,\nexpresses the opinion that evolution in\nindustrial and financial relations de\nmands a world peace. Evolution goes\non by superhuman methods and as it\ngrows more complex becomes harder to\nunderstand. Even the able Mr. Einstein\nrefrains from offering any views on the\nsubject.\nThere is a Mikado but he is not eager\nto assume personal responsibility for\nwhat goes on in the name of his empire.\nShooting Stars.\nBY PHILANDER JOHNSON.\nSuccessful Day.\nAs evening shadows gather \u2019round\nI pause in gratitude profound;\nI say, \u201cThe Fates my fortune bless.\nHooray 1 The day was a success!\u201d\nNo auto fatally drew nigh.\nNo airplane smote me from the sky.\nI knew Just when to go or stop,\nAnd quarreled with no crossing cop.\nI met no trace of robber band.\nNo burglar said, \u201cHold up your hands!\u201d\nAt night, I read of crimes at first,\nThen dozed and never knew the worst.\nSo, when the shadows gathered deep\nI, still intact, prepared for sleep,\nAnd said in reverent truthfulness,\n\u201cHooray! The day was a success!\u201d\nSpeed Impressions.\n\u201cDon't you sometimes think we are\nliving too fast?\u201d\n\u201cNo,\u201d answered Senator Sorghum. \"I\ndon\u2019t believe we are living too fast. We\nare merely talking too fast.\u201d\nJud Tunkins says if people must have\nmyths, he wishes they\u2019d cut out the\nwitches and stick to somebody pleasant,\nlike Santa Claus.\nContradictions.\nDebates in Congress bring us woe.\nOur doubts we cannot smother\nAs arguing statesmen fail to show\nBelief in one another.\nEqual Opportunity to Lose.\n\u201cI thought you rather liked my friend.\nYou know he believes in equality for\nwomen.\u201d\n\u201cYes,\u201d said Miss Cayenne. \u201cHe goes\ntoo far in that idea to suit me. When\nhe took me to the opera he insisted on\nmatching coins to determine which of\nus was to pay for the tickets and the\nsupper afterward.\u201d\n\u201cIf you tell wily what you know to be\nabsolutely true, said Hi Ho, the sage of\nChinatown, \u201cyou will meditate for six\nmonths before 'speaking five minutes.\u201d\nNo Escape.\nHe would not ride. He would not fly.\nAll safe in bed he sought to lie.\nHe found he could not beat the game.\nAn earthquake got him, Just the same.\n\u201cYou has to recognize luck,\u201d said Uncle\nEben. \u201cEven de sure-thing person dat\nstacks de cards has to be lucky not to\nget caught.\u201d\na\nFigures Show There Is\nNo Business Recession\nTo th\u00bb Editor of The Star;\nAfter reading the defense of several\ncolumnists, including Dorothy Thompson\nand Mark Sullivan, and also listening to\nthe news commentator, Lowell Thomas,\neach attempting to excuse undue em\nphasis upon the so-called business reces\nsion, I am moved to call attention to a\nnumber of facts which would Indicate\nthe reverse of a business recession.\nIn a recent broadcast Lowell Thomas\nsaid he recalled how he was required\nto minimize the depression of 1929-1932\nand emphasize all the cheerful news con\ncerning business in order to create the\nproper psychological atmosphere, but\nall to no avail. I might add that if Mr.\nThomas worked half as hard to serve\nthe best interests of the country at large\nduring the present situation as he did to\nserve the interests controlling his broad\ncasts during the Hoover depression he\ncould easily find good news to relate\nconcerning business increases in wages,\nsales, etc, as evidenced by the following\nfacts:\nA. A. Patton, Associated Press statis\ntician, in an article published in The\nSunday Star, December 26, stated that\nalthough 1937 was widely labeled as a\nyear which brought a renewed slump, it\nactually saw several industries set new\nhigh production records and others\ntouched historic peaks for all time.\nGroups topping all previous standards\nare as follows:\nCotton textile manufacturers, cotton\nfarmers also, due to favorable weather\nconditions, raised a bumper crop. The\nelectric branch of public utilities broke\nall previous records, as did electric re\nfrigeration and air conditioning, a new\nindustry. The great petroleum indus\ntry also counts 1937 a banner year; avi\nation pushed to new peaks; the shoe\noutput sets a new record. October as\nsemblies for automobile makers were the\nbest ever attained. During the first five\nmonths the steel industry turned out\nmore ingots than it did at the crest of\nthe greatest boom in history.\nHe further states: \"Also hanging up\nnew records were Treasury gold stocks\u2014\nat $2,804,000,000; demand deposits in the\ncountry's banks, $37,000,000,000 late in\nDecember compared with $16,000,000,000\nin 1929,\" more than double the 1929\nrecord.\nuoes au mis souna like a business re\ncession? If so, let's have some more like\nIt. Furthermore, while a great deal has\nbeen written about the income tax col\nlections falling below the estimates, little\nstress was laid on the fact that they did\nexceed collections for all years since 1929\nby millions of dollars. Also the income\nof the laboring classes as shown by So\ncial Securities statistics is greater than\nat any time since the boom years of\n1928 and 1929. All this means increased\npurchasing power by the masses as is\nevidenced by store sales, purchase of\nautomobiles, increased amounts paid out\nby banks on Christmas savings funds,\netc. Another headline in The Sunday\nStar of December 26 read: \u201cYule Busi\nness Tops Estimates, with South in the\nLead.\u201d\nFor lack of space, I have omitted\nfigures showing actual increases in above\nindustries, but these figures are available.\nI should therefore advise Lowell Thomas,\nDorothy Thompson and Mark Sullivan to\nmake a study of such statistics and give\na little publicity to all this good news.\nIt would indeed be a refreshing change\nfrom the dire forebodings in which they\nso frequently indulge.\nINEZ JUSTUS.\nProposed Farm-Control\nLegislation Is Suicidal\nTo the Idltor of The Star:\nI can no longer resist the urge to give\npublic expression to my views on what is\ntermed \u201cfarm control, \u201cfarm aid\" or\n\u201cfarm legislation.\u201d This is one of the\nmost important bills now before our leg\nislative bodies on Capitol Hill.\nThis question affects the economic life\nof vast multitudes of people entirely\noutside the farming class. We must\nadmit that approximately eighty per\ncent of our food and perhaps ninety-five\nper cent of our clothing are products of\nthe farm.\nAny legislation that carries crop limit\ning measures is unquestionably unjust.\nSuch a law would tend to discourage an\nambitious and progressive farmer. Again\nthe prosperous farmers are so far in the\nminority that comparatively few would\nreceive compensation for not cultivating\nten acres of the fifty acres they had in\nmind to plant or raising ten per cent\nleas stock.\nMany people who live on farms do not\nproduce sufficient to sustain life, and\nare compelled to buy from a brother\nfarmer at prices that are far above the\nlevel of his circumstances\u2014yet his Gov\nernment to whom he looks for protection\n\u2014collects his taxes and pays over to his\nbrother to keep the prices up on the very\nproducts he is compelled to buy.\nWhen we step outside the farm realm\nwe are confronted with the hordes of\nhuman beings who, for their very sub\nsistence, have to buy farm products. Is\nit just to collect taxes or revenues from\nthis vast multitude and pay a favored\nclass to keep the prices high on the\nnecessaries of life, that which is essen\ntial to keep soul and body together?\nGive the farmer a free hand\u2014remove\nany crop limitations\u2014and let him profit\nby volume of production with prices at a\nlevel within reach of the less favored.\nAlong these lines much might be ac\ncomplished toward reducing the number\nof unemployed, diminishing relief re\nquests and minimizing relief appropria\ntions.\nForestall this suicidal plan whereby we\npay the other fellow to keep the price\nhigh on the commodities which we are\ncompelled to buy. R. A. PEARSON.\nObjects to Beatty Story\nAbout South America\nTo the Editor of The Star:\nMr. Morgan M. Beatty's article in The\nWashington Sunday Star of November\n21 has been called tomy attention. I do\nnot question its main thesis, \u201cRadio Un\ndermining Monroe Doctrine,\u201d but when\nthe statement is made that South\nAmerican dictatorships are not Fascist\nthat calls for some explanation and\ni evidence. The unnamed authority for\nthis statement leaves himself a loophole,\nI It is true; he says they are \u201cnot Fascist\nin the Italian sense.\u201d Well, of course, no\nI nation is quite like another. What we\nare interested in is whether these coun\ntries are not practically Fascist dicta\ntorships. What country ever admitted\nbeing Fascist \u201cin the Italian sense\u201d?\nDid Germany? Or Franco\u2019s Spain?\nThis \"unofficial authority\u201d also speaks\nof Latin American countries \"that bear\nthe Communist stamp.\u201d I never heard\nbefore there were-any such South Amer\nican countries. Which ones are meant?\nWriters of Fascist sympathies are accus\ntomed to call loyalist Spain Communist,\nand even France is labeled Communistic,\nin fact Hitler and Mussolini call all\ndemocracies Communistic fn tendency.\nIt makes a difference who does the call\ning. HARRIET W. PATTERSON.\nSix for Two.\nFrom the Kalamazoo Gazette.\nA text book tells us there are only six\ntastes\u2014sweet, salt, sour, bitter, metallic,\nand alkaline. How about \"good\u201d and\n\u201cbad?\u201d\na\nTHIS AND THAT\nBY CHARLES E. TRACEWELL.\n\"Nobody.\u201d the man said, \"ever listens\nto symphonies.\n\u201cWhy,\u201d he continued, \"I turn them\ntilings off every time!\u201d\nNo doubt he was an honest, truthful\nman.\nHe clicked off his radio set every\ntime a symphony was broadcast.\nWhere he erred was in thinking that\nbecause he did so, others Invariably\ndid so.\n\nHe was a typical American.\nHence his naive belief that his own\nlikes and dislikes set the fashion.\nIt seems to be pretty difficult for a\ntrue 120 per cent American to believe\nthat his own tastes are not the national\nstandard.\nThe joke of the matter is that they\nare often enough to be discomfiting.\n\nYet as far as symphony music is\nconcerned, there can be little doubt that\nthe national broadcasts o\u00a3\u00bb the great\norchestras have been helpful.\nNo doubt there are thousands of per\nsons in this country who today would\nnot be quite so outspoken.\nAnd there are hundreds, where there\nused to be but one, perhaps, who really\nlike to listen to symphonic music,\nwhether in concert hall, over the radio,\nor from their own gramophones.\nThe radio undoubtedly has played its\npart.\nw w w w\nUniversal education, too, has done its\nshare.\nMany serious young persons have felt\nthat the masterpieces of symphonic\nliterature must be worth listening to,\nhence they have \"exposed\u201d themselves\nto them, always to their ultimate good.\nThe interesting thing is that often\nenough where one listens out of grim\nduty, a sense of real appreciation\nawakens, to be a life-long possession.\nWhere the outspoken gentleman erred\nwas in his belief that nobody ever lis\ntened to symphonies.\nHe may \"turn them off,\u201d but many do\nnot; many, as a matter of truth, \"turn\n\u2019em on\u201d where a few years ago they\nwould never have thought of doing so\nbold a thing.\n\nMusic is, of all the arts, the most\nelusive.\nWe are such a word-minded people\nthat we insist on talking about every\nthing we enjoy, and there is little the\ngreat average person can say about\nmusic.\nHe knows \"what he likes,\u201d and what\nhe does not like, or at least thinks he\ndoes.\nOften he finds out, to his great sur\nprise, that he does not know even that\nmuch about this art.\nWe were interested the other day in\nlooking over a list of phonograph records\nwhich a young man had purchased in\ntwo years.\nIt seemed a great deal of money, but\nit was far better than frittering it\naway, as the old folks used to say, on\nuseless and truly evanescent things.\nThis young man had a priceless pos\nsession in the newer recordings.\n\nWhat was particularly interesting\nabout it was that the long list included\nbut two of Beethoven\u2019s works.\nThis is natural. Beethoven is not the\nt\ncomposer of youth\u2019s young dreams. He\nis loved more by mature minds and\nhearts.\nThe day will come when this same\nyoung man, so in love with his Berlioz,\nhis Ravel, his Stravinsky, will find out\nthat he loves Beethoven more than all\nof them.\nHe would not believe that statement\nnow, but he will thirty years from now.\nThen he will realize that, as a young\nman, he really did not know \u201cwhat he\nliked,\u201d after all.\nHis judgments on music were the\njudgments of the young, and they are\nnot and cannot be the same as the\nJudgments of older people.\nIt is difficult to convince some persons\nthat music is thinking, but if it were\nnot it would have little appeal to those\nbeyond the jazz age.\nIt is emotional thinking, rather than\nintellectual thinking.\nIt is because thousands of persons\nmostly indulge in emotional thinking\nthat music makes such a great appeal\nto them.\nIt is because music is thought, of a\nsort, and that all of us think, in a way,\nand to a certain extent, that music of\nthe best quality has a chance to appeal\nto us sometime in our lives.\n\nThat is why one may grow in musical\nappreciation, and why the pure music,\nas it is called, of the symphony, is the\nlast growth along the road of apprecia\ntion.\nMany a person wno nonesuy Deneves\nthat nobody, positively nobody, cares for\nsuch music, in time will come to love\nit himself, much to his astonishment\nThis is one case in which a little\nfamiliarity is not a dangerous thing.\nA little familiarity, at first, is the only\nway to leam.\nIt is the same with music as with\nreading, writing, arithmetic.\nMaking garden, or anything else, it is\nalways the same, first a little, then a bit\nmore, then a great deal more.\nWhen the world goes back on that\nidea and tries to get something for\nnothing, it may achieve the something,\nbut the nothing will get its revenge, in\na peculiar way. For the something,\nbeing only half or one-fourth known, is\nnot valued, and hence is thrown away\nor lost.\n\nThose who shrink from the sym\nphonies must do the very easy thing of\nexposing themselves to them, now and\nthen.\nIt is an amazing thing, how' even the\ntrained listener may \u201cnot see a thing\u201d\nin a symphony, at first, only to find it\nopening up new beauties to him each\ntime he hears it.\nWe know a gentleman in this town\nwho loves Beethoven's third, the\n\u201cEroica,\u201d but says he cannot endure\nVaughan Williams\u2019 \u201cA London Sym\nphony.\u201d\nKnowing his real love of music, we\nfeel sure that if he listened to it twice\nin his own home, on the only record\ning. he would shortly come to appreciate\nit for a splendid work.\nA symphony is not mere sound and\nfury, but the quintessence of musical\nthinking. It represents plan and order;\nit means something great, something in\ntensely human and therefore hopeful\nand alive.\nSTARS, MEN AND ATOMS\nNotebook of Science Progress in Field,\nLaboratory and Study.\nBY THOMAS R. HENRY.\nOctober the 11th, 1492, is a half-way\nmark in the white colonization of the\nNew World.\nOn the very day Columbus landed, it\nis very likely, a little band of beleaguered\nCaucasians far to the northward were\nmaking a last futile stand against mas\nsacre and annihilation.\nThey were native-born Americans with\nan ancestry extending backward for five\ncenturies on American soil. They were\nChristians with fine churches and mon\nasteries. Their last bishop, it so hap\npens, was named at Rome the very year\nColumbus sailed from Spain. He never\nsaw his bishopric.\nThis was the end. They were a weak\nened, inbred, probably degenerate lot.\nFar to the southward, in a land they\nnever had dreamed of, another 500 years\nof American history was starting.\nThis, of course, is an old story. The\nwhite men were the last survivors of the\nNorse colony in Greenland. For more\nthan a century, at least, they had been\ncompletely out of touch with Europe.\nTheir soil had lost its fertility. Their\nclimate had become severer, their sum\nmers shorter. Their cattle, sheep and\npigs had perished. Out of the north\nthe final scourge had descended\u2014groups\nof dark, crafty little savages relentless in\ntheir hate.\nThrough all the five centuries this\nmenace had hung over the colony. Every\nnow and then the white men had come\nin contact with the Eskimos. They\nhated them as foreigners, savages and\nheathen, they probably had slaughtered\nthem mercilessly when they had an\nopportunity. As a result they had\nturned the world\u2019s friendliest people into\nimplacable foes, awaiting an opportu\nnity for revenge.\nThe white men perished. Their vil\nlages and farmsteads crumbled into\nheaps of stone. The very existence of\nthe colony dropped out of memory for\n300 years. It was a closed episode in\nhistory. Far to the southward the new\nworld was rediscovered and recon\nquered.\n_. _ f_ _i.1_J __\nXu IS A glllll JUIVt Ull WiV V\u00bbM4 IIV/IOVIIIVU,\nThe chief significance of their colony to\nday, it seems, is that it provides a date\nfrom which can be reconstructed a crude\nchronology of the prehistoric past of\nthe very savages they despised and who\nfinally murdered them. Can one im\nagine that, a thousand years hence,\narcheologists will consider the great\ncities of the United States long since\nburied in ruins chiefly as means of es\ntablishing dates in the continuous his\ntory of the Indians? The cases are not\nexactly parallel, of course, but what has\nactually happened probably would have\nseemed as absurd to the Greenland\nNorsemen at the height of their pros\nperity.\nIt is known that Greenland was dis\ncovered by Erick the Red about the year\n1000 and that colonization from Iceland\nstarted soon afterward. It is also known\nthat in 1350 came the first formidable\nEskimo attack and that the Norse set\ntlements were destroyed during the next\ncentury. Hence Norse objects, such as\nchess pieces, eating utensils and church\nbell metal found in ancient Eskimo habi\ntation sites, make it possible to date the\nsites themselves.\nThe story of efforts to reconstruct a\npre-history of the Eskimo is told by Dr.\nTherkel Mathiassen of the Danish Na\ntional Museum In the annual report of\nthe Smithsonian Institution. The first\nA\nexcavations were at a village site in the\nCanadian Arctic north of Hudson Bay.\nThere the artifacts of an Eskimo culture\nwere uncovered which showed signs of\ngreat antiquity and differed materially\nfrom the articles used in the region to\nday. This site could not be dated.\nNext came the excavation of a site in\nNorthwest Greenland with much the\nsame type of culture but with variations\nshowing that it was considerably more\nrecent. Here were found objects made\nof church bell metal, showing that these\npeople had come in contact with the\nNorsemen. The paucity of objects, how\never, reveals that the contact was quite\ncursory. It must have been quite early\nin the Norse occupation.\nThen sites were excavated quite close\nto the Norse settlements themselves.\nThese contained many more European\nobjects. They must date from the time\nwhen the Eskimo, descending out of the\nNorth, were making successful attacks on\nthe white settlements.\nWhile the Norsemen were on the\nSouthern coast the hated Eskimo cer\ntainly could not have passed by them to\nsettle along the East coast. They never\ncould have passed over the Greenland\nice sheet. Consequently East coast ruins\ncertainly date from some time subsequent\nto the annihilation of the Scandinavians.\nIn this way. Dr. Mathiassen points\nout, a sort of chronology by centuries of\nthe history of the dominant people of the\nPar North can be built up.\nOpposes Separate Board\nFor Recreational Activities\nTo the Editor of The Star:\nI am glad to see that the citizens\u2019\nassociations are waking up to the danger\nof the proposal which is before the com\nmunity to divide education by attempt\ning to remove from the schools their\ncommunity and recreational activities,\nputting this phase of educational work\nunder a separate board. The proposed\nplan is like earlier efforts to have sepa\nrate boards for high schools. It would\nharm both education and recreation,\nresulting in years of conflict, waste and\narrested development.\nFor many years I have been interested\nin this problem of recreation and have\nmade inquiries in different cities as to\nthe manner of administering public rec\nreation. Clearly allowing for occasional\nexceptions, recreation is best admin\nistered in those cities where it is com\npletely under the jurisdiction of the\nBoard of Education. Under that plan\npersonnel is more carefully selected and\nbetter qualified; facilities are used to\nbetter advantage; the relationship to\nhome life is better; study and leisure are\nbetter co-ordinated and are focused\nmore effectively toward well-rounded\ncharacter development. In 1918 a nota\nble committee of the National Education\nAssociation on which the late President\nCharles W. Eliot of Harvard was a lead\ning member, pointed out that education\nfor leisure is an increasingly important\npart of the school's task. Recreation is\na phase of education. It should be In\ncharge of people thoroughly trained in\nchild growth and development and in\nmethods of educational work and under\nsupervision of educational authorities.\nLet every parent, teacher and citizen\ngive thought to this issue and bring the\nmatter to the attention of members of\nCongress. The need of government to\nday is toward greater unity and effi\nciency, not toward increased division\nand confusion.\nJOY ELMER MORGAN.\na\nANSWERS TO\nQUESTIONS\nBY FREDERIC J. HA SKIN.\nA reader can get the answer to any\nquestion of fact by writing The Evening\nStar Information Bureau, Frederic J.\nHaskin, director, Washington, D. C.\nPlease inclose stamp for reply.\nQ. How much money has Japan bor\nrowed from foreign countries during the\npresent undeclared war?\u2014W. P.\nA. No large loan has been floated by\nJapan in any foreign country.\nQ. Do many automobiles run Into the\nsides of trains from darkness to day\nlight?\u2014E. P. F.\nA. In the year 1936 the total number\nof such accidents was 1,108.\nQ. Who first said, \u201cWhen a man bites\na dog, that\u2019s news\u201d?\u2014B. H. K.\nA. It is usually attributed to Charles\nA. Dana, editor of the New York Sun.\nBurton Stevenson, in his \u201cHome Book of\nQuotations,\u201d says that the evidence ac\ntually favors J. B. Bogart, who was city\neditor from 1873-1890.\nQ. Is rosin used in paper making?\u2014\nJ. M. W.\nA. It is used in sizing paper. This\nis one of the largest uses of rosin.\nQ. What is the total valuation of the\nUnited States Capitol and grounds as\nit now stands?\u2014M. A.\nA. The architect's office of the Capitol\nsays that the assessed value of the Cap\nitol Building and grounds in 1935 was\nestimated at $58,000,000. The land area\nis valued at $20,000,000.\nQ. How\u2019 should the ivory keyboard of\nthe piano be cleaned?\u2014S. J.\nA. The Etude says that the best\nmethod is to moisten a cloth slightly\nwith pure alcohol. Be sure that the\ncloth does not come in contact with the\nwood of the case, as that will injure the\nvarnish.\nQ. Does lightning create an air vac\nuum, with thunder the sound of the air\nrushing back into it?\u2014W. V. E.\nA. Lightning does not produce a\nvacuum in the atmosphere, although\nthere is some rarefaction of the air along\nthe path of the discharge because of\nthe intense heating. The sound known\nas thunder, which accompanies a flash\nof lightning, is caused by the violent ex\nplosion of the air along the path of the\ndischarge. The explosion results from\nintense heating and the disintegration\nof molecules to atoms and atoms to elec\ntrons and ions. The rolling of thunder\nis owing chiefly to the crookedness of\nthe lightning path and to the inequality\nof the distance of its various portions\nfrom the observer.\nQ. What does it c06t to make a new\nstamp issue?\u2014E. V.\nA. The Post Office Department says\nthat it averages $300 to $500, depending\non the nature of the design and the\namount of engraving.\nQ. Did Woodrow Wilson practice law\nIn Atlanta. Ga.?\u2014H. J. H.\nA. Woodrow Wilson arrived In At\nlanta on June 1, 1882, and formed the\nfirm of Renick L Wilson, with offices\nat 48 Marietta street. His certificate to\npractice in the State courts of Georgia\nis dated October 19, 1882. His practice\nin Atlanta was not particularly success\nful and he left In September, 1883, to go\nto Baltimore.\nQ. Does Chinese writing run from\nright to left or up and down the page?\n\u2014E. W.\nA. Chinese writing reads from top to\nbottom in columns. The columns read\nfrom right to left.\nQ. What does the carillon in Rich\nmond, Va., commemorate?\u2014M. S.\nA. It is a World War memorial.\nQ. How old was Queen Marie of Ru\nmania when she married Ferdinand?\u2014\nW. H.\nA. She was seventeen years old at the\ntime of her marriage.\nQ. How many district courts were\nthere in the United States in 1789?\u2014\nJ. G.\nA. There were thirteen in that year.\nQ. How much money did Jay Gould\nleave?\u2014E. J. K.\nA. At his death. In 1892. he left an\nestate of eighty million dollars.\nQ. What kind of an animal is the\nnilgai?\u2014E. W.\nA. It is the largest of the Indian\nantelopes, somewhat intermediate be\ntween the deer and the ox. About the\nsize of a mule, it is bluish gray in color\nand stands 4\u2019i feet high at the shoulder,\nwith an oxlike head and body, long,\nslender legs, and small, short horns.\nQ. What is meant by the musical\nterm stringendo?\u2014H. J.\nA. It means somewhat hurried.\nQ. Where is Nepal?\u2014W. J. H.\nA. Nepal is a kingdom in the Himalaya\nMountains which lies between Tibet and\nBritish India. The dominant native race\nis that of the Gurkhas.\nQ. How long did St. Simeon live on\na pillar?\u2014B. E.\nA. This Syrian ascetic is said to have\nlived for 35 years on a small platform\non top of a high pillar.\nQ. What became of the son of Na\npoleon and the Countess Walewska?\n\u2014R. M.\nA. He was bom in Poland In 1810\nand died at the age of 58. Ha became\na naturalized French subject and held\nimportant government offices during'\nthe second empire.\nQ. When was gold first coined as\nmoney?\u2014W. B.\nA. Gold was first coined as money by\nKing Croesus of Lydia in the 6th cen\ntury B.C.\nQ. Where is the street called\nStraight?\u2014J. K. W.\nA. It is in Damascus. It traverses the\ncity from east gate to west gate, but has\nbecome crooked by the encroachment at\nbazaars and shops.\nA Rhyme at Twilight\nBy\nGertrude Brooke Hamilton.\nBereaved.\nNo sunset glowed in the sky tonight.\nNo red and gold in the short twilight,\nDark came with biting cold.\nI draw my curtains, and pull my chair\nUp close to the cozy fireplace, where\nYou used to dream of old.\nYou loved to toss on the dying fire\nFresh logs, to watch them blaze up higher\nAnd nestle in the glow,\nThen, resting your head against my\nknee.\nPicture the dreams only you could see,\nDreams only you could know.\nAh. love, what joy for us both tonight\nIf you nestled still in our warm firelight!\ni","height":"31296","width":"22652"}}
